In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October 2012 as National Substance Abuse Prevention Month. He acknowledges the negative impacts of alcohol and drug abuse, such as diminished achievement in schools and increased risks on the roads and in communities. The President emphasizes that substance abuse is preventable and highlights his administration's efforts to promote a balanced approach to drug control, focusing on evidence-based public health and safety reforms. The administration has invested in outreach programs to educate young Americans about substance abuse and has worked to address the issue of prescription drug abuse. The President encourages all Americans to play a role in preventing drug and alcohol abuse, particularly parents, guardians, teachers, faith-based groups, healthcare providers, law enforcement officials, and local leaders. He calls for comprehensive substance abuse prevention efforts within communities and urges everyone to engage in appropriate programs and activities.